<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex</i> <i>parryi</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>albidus</i> and/or <i>Sarcobatus</i> <i>vermiculatus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Allenrolfea</i> <i>occidentalis</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>canescens</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>spinifera</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>torreyi</i>, <i>Chrysothamnus</i> <i>viscidiflorus</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i>, <i>Frankenia</i> <i>salina</i>, <i>Kochia</i> <i>californica</i> and <i>Suaeda</i> <i>moquinii</i>. Associated herbs include <i>Bromus</i> <i>tectorum</i>, <i>Cleomella</i> <i>obtusifolia</i>, <i>Distichlis</i> <i>spicata</i>, <i>Leymus</i> <i>cinereus</i>, <i>Salsola</i> <i>tragus</i>, <i>Sporobolus</i> <i>airoides</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 3 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is variable and may be grassy. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> > 2% absolute cover and no other shrub > cover in the shrub canopy (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> â‰¥ 2% absolute cover and other shrubs may co-dominate in the shrub canopy; herbs may occur at higher cover than the shrubs (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Atriplex parryi</i> > 2% absolute cover and > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Chrysothamnus albidus </i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (VegCamp 2014b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> is characteristically present in the shrub layer with as little as 1% absolute cover (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> >30% cover in the shrub layer with <i>Artemisia tridentata, Atriplex confertifolia</i>, and/or <i>Chrysothamnus</i> spp. (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Dry lake beds, old lake beds perched above current drainages, lagoon bars, badlands, plains, alkali stream terraces, stable sand dunes, and barrier beaches. The USFWS Wetland Inventory (2012 national list) recognizes <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> as a FACU plant and <i>Atriplex parryi</i> as a FAC plant. </div>
</div>

        
