<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus </i>is a long-lived, winter-deciduous, microphyllous, facultative halophyte that tolerates alkaline and saline soils. Seeds mature in the fall, and fruits dehisce in the winter. Seeds germinate under conditions of warm temperatures and long periods of soil moisture. Individual plant and population responses to different osmotic potentials and different salt concentrations suggest much ecotypic variation (Anderson 2004b). <br/>
<br/>
In general, stands of this alliance are dominated or codominated by <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> and shrubby codominants can vary by region and site salinity. Additionally, <i>Atriplex parryi</i> and <i>Chrysothamnus albidus</i> occupy similar environmental settings as <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> within California and are considered part of this alliance when dominant, including in the Owens Valley. Outside of California, these taxa have not been observed with <i>Sarcobatus, </i>such as in south Hot Creek Valley in Nevada (Beatley 1976). This is one of several alliances in the alkali sink habitat, including the <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis, Distichlis spicata, </i>and <i>Suaeda moquinii </i>alliances. <i>Allenrolfea occidentalis </i>tolerates higher salt concentrations than <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus </i>(MacMahon and Wagner 1985). Perennial forbs are typically sparse, but annual grasses (oftentimes nonnative species) may be seasonally present to abundant (NatureServe 2019). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
