    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gg, Gi, Gm). Small stands of <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus </i>occur in alkali basins near Alturas with <i>Artemisia tridentata.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa-b, Ad, Ag, Ai). Stands are locally associated with upper playa flats and low dunes along the margins of Pleistocene lake beds with <i>S. vermiculatus </i>and <i>Atriplex parryi </i>at Owens Lake (Thomas et al. 2004, Reyes et al. 2020a) and <i>S. vermiculatus </i>at Edwards Air Force Base (Charlton 2000a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Da, Df, Dh-i). Stands of <i>S. vermiculatus </i>exist in Carson Valley and Mono Lake Basin. Other stands of <i>S. vermiculatus, A. parryi, </i>and <i>Chrysothamnus albidus</i> occur in upper Owens Valley at Fish Slough (Odion et al. 1992a, VegCamp 2014b).</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba, Bc-d). Stands of <i>S. vermiculatus </i>occur in Surprise Valley and Honey Lake Basins.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-c). Stands of <i>S. vermiculatus</i> and <i> A. parryi</i> occur in Death Valley National Park (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Shrubs are important as fall and winter browse for livestock and wildlife. Stems regenerate vigorously by sprouting after disturbance, and populations may increase with grazing (Anderson 2004b). However, <i>S. vermiculatus</i> may be moderately poisonous to livestock, especially in the fall. Fire will top-kill <i>S. vermiculatus</i>, but the shrub will promptly resprout from the root crown (NatureServe 2019).

Since stands occur on sites that are intermittently flooded, stands may be reduced by evaporite mining, groundwater pumping, and drought/drying trends. Phreatophytic plants such as <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> and <i>Sporobolus airodes</i> are deep-rooted plants that depend on groundwater supplies, whereby groundwater pumping and drought in the Owens Valley in particular have been correlated with declines of phreatophytic plant cover and concomittant increases of nonphreatophyic plants including non-natives (Elmore et al. 2003). </div>
</div>

    

    

